Mediacom offers a simple, affordable way to help students get quality home internet, Connect-2-Compete.

Who is eligible for Mediacom Connect-2-Compete?
Your household may qualify if you meet all of the following criteria:

- Live in a community (or area) where Mediacom offers internet service (generally, Mediacom's network is available within city boundaries; we can check to see which addresses are located along our extensive broadband network)
-Have at least one child who qualifies for free or reduced-price school lunch through the National School Lunch Program (NSLP)
-Have NOT subscribed to Mediacom internet service in the past 90 days
-Do not have an outstanding Mediacom bill or unreturned equipment.*

https://www.franklincountyschools.org/cms/lib/FL01803254/Centricity/Domain/121/Mediacom%20Internet%20Special.pdf

https://mediacomc2c.com/frequently-asked-questions.aspx

post_text:
COVID-19 Update from FDOH-Gulf/Franklin and FDOE:
When you can be around others after a positive COVID19 test?
If you think or know you had COVID-19 and had symptoms, you can be with others after at least 10 days since symptoms first appeared AND at least 24 hours have passed with no fever without fever-reducing medication AND symptoms have improved. If you tested positive for COVID-19 but had no symptoms, you can be with others after 10 days have passed since your test.
According to the CDC, a person who has had and recovered from COVID-19 may have low levels of virus in their bodies for up to 3 months after diagnosis. This means that if the person who has recovered from COVID-19 is retested within 3 months of initial infection, they may continue to have a positive test result, even though they are not spreading COVID-19. Meaning, they are no longer infectious to others.

Visit the link below for the full statement from FDOH-Gulf/Franklin and FDOE:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/103NQto5cSyuURwtS3t7iQBBUQDRCtSP3iUcw2utlpF8/edit?usp=sharing

PRESS RELEASE
RE: DISTRICT RESPONSE TO POSITIVE COVID-19 CASES

The Franklin County School District has been notified by the Health Department of active contact tracing investigations related to confirmed positive cases of COVID-19 on the FCS Campus. District staff is taking steps to mitigate the spread after receiving notification. All individuals having direct contact with those who tested positive will be required to voluntarily self-quarantine for a period of 14 days. These individuals will remain at home until cleared by public health officials.

https://www.franklincountyschools.org/cms/lib/FL01803254/Centricity/Domain/36/Press%20Release%208.21.20.pdf

A shoutout to Seahawk Nation! Thank you, parents, students and staff for a great 1st day back at school. We are confident that our morning routine will steadily improve over the next several weeks as we all adjust to new school times, drop off locations and the required temperature checks.
We have identified a few areas of concern related to transportation and will make the needed adjustments to improve the flow of traffic as well as afternoon arrival times.
Please see a message from the transportation department:

Our drivers were so excited to see your children today and although there were a few setbacks we do believe we have identified the issues and will work diligently to have them corrected. Please take a moment to log into your parent portal and make any corrections to student addresses to help us get your child home safely. Also, please fill out the bus ridership form sent home with your child today and return it to your bus driver on Monday.

post_text:
The Superintendent has published a press release concerning the start date for students and will be recommending to shift the four teacher professional development days to the beginning of the school year resulting in an August 14th start date for students. A revised school calendar will be published following the next School Board meeting.

‚ÄúWhile our campuses and buses have been cleaned and sanitized and plans for both on-campus and virtual instruction are in place, I believe that spending our professional development days in August will provide our faculty and staff with the support and training through our local Health Department, to be better prepared to welcome our students back to school safely." said Superintendent Yoder.

Thank you for your continued patience, support, and partnership as we move forward with safely preparing to welcome our students back to school.

**July 28th Update: The FHSAA has reversed its decision and will postpone the fall start date. Football conditioning will continue every Monday, Tuesday & Thursday from 4:45-7pm. Beginning the Week of 8/17 we will go every day after school until 5:30pm. An updated game schedule will be published at a later date. ******
We are excited that the FHSAA has approved the fall calendar and sports will resume as scheduled.
"Sports provide a positive outlet for students and we are committed to doing our part to ensure the safety of all student-athletes by following CDC, SMAC and local guidelines as we navigate this new normal together," said Coach Strunk. #GoSeahawk

post_text:
The Franklin County School District was made aware of two employees testing positive for COVID-19. Both employees were asymptomatic and took immediate steps to mitigate the spread after receiving test results. All employees having direct contact with those who tested positive have been required to voluntarily self-quarantine for a period of 14 days.

Superintendent Yoder has worked in conjunction with the local health department to ensure that all recommended protocols are followed as the safety and wellbeing of our students and staff is our top priority.

We are thankful that our staff members had minimal or no symptoms but want to assure you that all possible measures to maintain a safe learning environment will be taken to protect all stakeholders.

A link is provided below to view the full press release.

post_text:
The 2019-20 school year might have ended under the most unusual of circumstances yet these amazing students (Alex Itzkovitz, FCS 10th Grader & Mya Itzkovitz, ABC 8th Grader) have combined technology and the lessons they have learned to provide real world solutions to our community during these difficult times.
Ms. Mathis, our HS Science Teacher, approached Alex with the idea and with the support of Superintendent Yoder, provided the 3D printer from her classroom. Alex and his sister researched and created several different styles of face shields and provided their finished products to our local hospital.
We are very proud of these students and their willingness to think outside the box and fill a need in our community. Help us congratulate them on a job well done!

post_text:
Franklin County School District Back-to-School Survey

As we move forward during this Covid-19 pandemic, it is important to Franklin County School District that we solicit feedback from our stakeholders wherever possible. We do not yet know about guidelines for reopening schools that may be issued by the Florida Department of Education, Florida Governor DeSantis, or the federal government but we're planning and brainstorming as much as we can in the meantime.

Please take two minutes to give us your feedback by answering the questions in the survey below. Your answers are strictly anonymous and the information you provide will be used to help guide us if there are local decisions to be made about back-to-school.

The deadline to complete this survey is Tuesday, May 19th.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/R9SHDYR

Community Business Leaders:
You have always been there for our program and our kids. You‚Äôve been with us through the ups and downs. Every year your donations have helped to improve our program. Our students are able to play this great game with the finest equipment because of your generous contributions.
During these tough times you might not be able to give like you have in the past and that‚Äôs ok. We will still display your sign at the stadium. This year we are not setting a strict price on stadium signs. We ask that you give what you can, when you can.

PARENT LUNCH & LEARN: HELPING YOUR CHILD COPE
Date: March 27, 2020 Time: 11:30am-12:30pm EST
Location: Virtual Webinar

The Florida Diagnostic and Learning Resources System has partnered with the Florida Virtual School to present a session to support parents during this tumultuous and stressful time. Please join our conversation with mental health experts about best ways to talk with your children about COVID-19, in an age appropriate way. Learn tips for managing our own emotions while helping your children cope with the stress and anxiety of these uncertain times. Participants will gain knowledge regarding best practices and tips for helping their families cope with the mental distress of COVID-19.
Register: bit.ly/LL3272020

post_text:
Let's stay in shape FCS!

Franklin County
Athletics
At Home Workout from Coach Strunk

‚Ä¢ 1 Deck of Cards, 13 cards per set.
‚Ä¢ Ace or Facecard = 11 Reps, otherwise do the number of the card.
‚Ä¢ Example: 7 of Diamonds would = 7 push-ups
‚Ä¢ Your workout is not complete until you have gone through the whole deck of cards.
‚Ä¢ Warm-Up of 150 Jumping Jacks before each workout.

Monday:
Hearts = Mountain Climbers
Diamond = Push-Ups
Spades = Body Squats
Clubs = Crunches

Wednesday:
Hearts = Front Lunges
Diamond = Decline Push-Ups
Spades = Squat Jumps
Clubs = Burpees

Friday:
Hearts = Reverse Lunges
Diamonds = Push-Ups
Spades = Dips
Clubs = Chair Step-ups

Dear parents and guardians,

In an effort to keep our families up to date and informed we are asking that all contact information is current in our student information system (FOCUS). If any contact information needs to be updated please contact data entry to ensure you will be notified as information comes forth regarding school activities. You may call 850-670-2810 or email Elementary data entry jtowns@franklincountyschools.org and middle/high data entry sbuffkin@franklincountyschools.org.

We are working on an instructional continuity and distance learning plan as required by the Florida Department of Education and will provide updates as we continue to seek guidance from state officials.

We encourage you to read the latest press release from the Department of Education with the following link.

Franklin County public schools will now be closed through April 15th.

Today at 4:45pm, the Florida Department of Education held an emergency conference call with all Superintendents in the state to extend the mandatory closure through April 15th.

The district and school administration are diligently working to develop a comprehensive plan to support our students‚Äô continuity of learning.

In an effort to effectively prepare to provide continuing educational support to our students during this extended school closure, we are asking for assistance from parents and guardians in completing a survey regarding access to internet connectivity.

Please click on the link below to complete the survey and stay connected through our Facebook and website for further information as it becomes available.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/Q82Q2S8

The 2019-20 Seahawk Yearbook is on sale for $50.00 until March 16 at 11:59 p.m. On March 17th the yearbooks will increase and remain at $75.00. Yearbooks can be purchased online at https://www.balfour.com/florida/eastpoint/franklin-county-school/yearbook-packages

Senior ads, special tributes to passing Seahawks, and business ads can also be purchased using the same link. You must design your own page; the instructions will come from the site once you click the size of the page you want. It will take 24 hours to process the payment and then grant you access to edit your ad (page). Also, please note these are separate purchases.

Full page - $150.00
Half Page - $75.00
No quarter size offered or available
Yearbook - $50.00 until sale ends ($75.00)

If you have questions please contact our yearbook sponsor, Ms. Morgan Martin, at mmartin@franklincountyschools.org

Franklin County School will host the Middle School District Tournament tomorrow, March 10th at home. The Seahawks will play Wewa at 1:00 p.m. All middle and high school students in good standing per the student code of conduct will be allowed to attend, with a suggested donation of $1. Blountstown will play Hosford at 3, and the championship game is at 5. We encourage the community to come out and support our middle school team. ALL visitors must check in through the front office and receive a badge for entrance into the game, as this event is being hosted during the school day.
